      <h1 class="mb-4">Antenatal & Postnatal Care</h1>
      <p class="lead mb-4">Comprehensive guidance for healthy pregnancy, labor preparation, and postpartum recovery to support you through your journey to motherhood.</p>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Antenatal Care Timeline</h5>
          
          <p>Regular prenatal care is essential for monitoring both maternal and fetal health throughout pregnancy.</p>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="antenatalAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFirstTrimester">
                <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFirstTrimester" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseFirstTrimester">
                  First Trimester (Weeks 1-12)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseFirstTrimester" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingFirstTrimester" data-bs-parent="#antenatalAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <h6>Key Appointments:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>First Prenatal Visit (6-8 weeks):</strong> Confirmation of pregnancy, due date calculation, medical history review, physical exam, blood tests</li>
                    <li><strong>10-12 Week Visit:</strong> Check blood pressure and weight, listen for fetal heartbeat, optional genetic screening tests</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <h6>Screenings & Tests:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Blood type and Rh factor</li>
                    <li>Complete blood count (CBC)</li>
                    <li>Urine analysis</li>
                    <li>Infection screenings (HIV, hepatitis B, syphilis)</li>
                    <li>Genetic carrier screening</li>
                    <li>Optional: Nuchal translucency (NT) scan and first-trimester screening for chromosomal abnormalities</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <h6>Health Focus:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Starting prenatal vitamins with folic acid</li>
                    <li>Managing morning sickness</li>
                    <li>Addressing fatigue</li>
                    <li>Avoiding harmful substances (alcohol, tobacco, certain medications)</li>
                    <li>Understanding pregnancy nutrition basics</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingSecondTrimester">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseSecondTrimester" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSecondTrimester">
                  Second Trimester (Weeks 13-27)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseSecondTrimester" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingSecondTrimester" data-bs-parent="#antenatalAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <h6>Key Appointments:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>Regular Check-ups:</strong> Every 4 weeks</li>
                    <li><strong>Anatomy Scan (18-22 weeks):</strong> Detailed ultrasound examining baby's organs and development</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <h6>Screenings & Tests:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Maternal serum screening (quad screen) for birth defects</li>
                    <li>Glucose screening test (24-28 weeks) for gestational diabetes</li>
                    <li>Optional: Amniocentesis (15-20 weeks) if indicated</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <h6>Health Focus:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Monitoring weight gain</li>
                    <li>Beginning pregnancy exercises</li>
                    <li>Understanding fetal movement patterns</li>
                    <li>Planning for maternity leave</li>
                    <li>Considering childbirth education classes</li>
                    <li>Addressing common discomforts (back pain, round ligament pain)</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThirdTrimester">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThirdTrimester" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThirdTrimester">
                  Third Trimester (Weeks 28-40)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseThirdTrimester" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThirdTrimester" data-bs-parent="#antenatalAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <h6>Key Appointments:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>Weeks 28-36:</strong> Check-ups every 2 weeks</li>
                    <li><strong>Weeks 36-40:</strong> Weekly check-ups</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <h6>Screenings & Tests:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Group B Streptococcus (GBS) screening (35-37 weeks)</li>
                    <li>Non-stress tests or biophysical profiles (if needed)</li>
                    <li>Monitoring for preeclampsia (blood pressure, urine tests)</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <h6>Health Focus:</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Recognizing signs of labor</li>
                    <li>Monitoring fetal movement daily</li>
                    <li>Creating a birth plan</li>
                    <li>Preparing for breastfeeding</li>
                    <li>Hospital pre-registration</li>
                    <li>Managing late pregnancy discomforts (insomnia, heartburn, swelling)</li>
                    <li>Infant care and safety education</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
