      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Preparing for Labor and Birth</h5>
          
          <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <h6>Birth Plan Considerations</h6>
              <p>A birth plan helps communicate your preferences to your healthcare team. Consider including:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Labor environment preferences (lighting, music, movement)</li>
                <li>Pain management preferences (medication, natural techniques)</li>
                <li>Support people present during labor and delivery</li>
                <li>Preferences for interventions (continuous monitoring, IV fluids)</li>
                <li>Preferences for immediate newborn care</li>
                <li>Feeding plans for baby</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-muted"><em>Remember that a birth plan is a guide, not a contract. Stay flexible as circumstances may require adjustments.</em></p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <h6>Signs of Labor</h6>
              <p><strong>Early Labor Signs:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Mucus plug discharge ("bloody show")</li>
                <li>Water breaking (amniotic fluid release)</li>
                <li>Regular contractions that increase in intensity</li>
                <li>Persistent lower back pain and cramping</li>
              </ul>
              
              <p><strong>When to Go to the Hospital:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Contractions 5 minutes apart, lasting 1 minute, for 1 hour (5-1-1 rule)</li>
                <li>Water breaking, even without contractions</li>
                <li>Heavy vaginal bleeding</li>
                <li>Decreased fetal movement</li>
                <li>Severe headache or visual changes</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Pain Management Options</h6>
          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Method</th>
                  <th>Description</th>
                  <th>Pros</th>
                  <th>Cons</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Epidural</td>
                  <td>Medication injected into space around spinal nerves</td>
                  <td>Effective pain relief; allows rest; can still feel pressure to push</td>
                  <td>May limit mobility; potential for blood pressure drop; may prolong pushing stage</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Nitrous Oxide</td>
                  <td>Inhaled gas mixture</td>
                  <td>Self-administered; wears off quickly; doesn't affect infant</td>
                  <td>Partial pain relief only; possible nausea or dizziness</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>IV Pain Medication</td>
                  <td>Opioids delivered through IV</td>
                  <td>Quick relief; allows rest between contractions</td>
                  <td>Short-term effect; potential drowsiness; timing restrictions</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Breathing Techniques</td>
                  <td>Controlled breathing patterns</td>
                  <td>No side effects; can be used anywhere; gives sense of control</td>
                  <td>Requires practice; may not be sufficient for intense labor</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Hydrotherapy</td>
                  <td>Laboring in water</td>
                  <td>Reduces pain perception; promotes relaxation; aids mobility</td>
                  <td>Not available in all settings; may slow labor if used too early</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Massage & Counter-pressure</td>
                  <td>Physical techniques to reduce pain</td>
                  <td>No side effects; promotes partner involvement</td>
                  <td>Requires support person; effectiveness varies</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Postnatal Care</h5>
          
          <div class="alert alert-info mb-4">
            <h6 class="alert-heading">The Fourth Trimester</h6>
            <p class="mb-0">The first 12 weeks after birth, often called the "fourth trimester," is a critical time of adjustment and recovery for both mother and baby. Proper care during this period sets the foundation for long-term health and wellbeing.</p>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Maternal Recovery Timeline</h6>
          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Timeframe</th>
                  <th>Physical Recovery</th>
                  <th>Emotional Adjustment</th>
                  <th>Recommended Care</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>First Week</td>
                  <td>Vaginal discharge (lochia), perineal pain or C-section recovery, breast engorgement, afterpains</td>
                  <td>Baby blues (tearfulness, mood swings), adjustment to new role, sleep deprivation</td>
                  <td>Rest, hydration, pain management, perineal care, limited stairs/lifting, help with baby care</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Weeks 2-6</td>
                  <td>Continued healing, decreased bleeding, initial hormonal stabilization</td>
                  <td>Establishing new routines, potential vulnerability to postpartum mood disorders</td>
                  <td>Gradually increasing activity, balanced nutrition, scheduled rest periods, social support</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>6 Weeks</td>
                  <td>Postpartum check-up, initial healing complete for most women</td>
                  <td>Ongoing adjustment, relationship changes</td>
                  <td>Comprehensive physical exam, contraception planning, gradual return to exercise</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Weeks 6-12</td>
                  <td>Continued internal healing, hormonal regulation</td>
                  <td>Building confidence in parenting, relationship adjustments</td>
                  <td>Self-care routines, exercise program, addressing any ongoing physical concerns</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          
          <h6 class="mt-4">Breastfeeding Support</h6>
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <p><strong>Getting Started:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Initiate breastfeeding within first hour after birth if possible</li>
                <li>Learn proper latch techniques to prevent nipple pain</li>
                <li>Feed on demand (typically 8-12 times per day)</li>
                <li>Watch for hunger cues (rooting, hand-to-mouth, sucking motions)</li>
              </ul>
              
              <p><strong>Common Challenges:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Nipple soreness and cracking</li>
                <li>Engorgement</li>
                <li>Blocked ducts</li>
                <li>Concerns about milk supply</li>
                <li>Mastitis (breast infection)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <p><strong>Resources for Support:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Lactation consultants (IBCLC)</li>
                <li>La Leche League meetings</li>
                <li>Postpartum doulas</li>
                <li>Hospital breastfeeding clinics</li>
                <li>WIC breastfeeding support programs</li>
              </ul>
              
              <div class="alert alert-success">
                <p class="mb-0"><strong>Remember:</strong> Fed is best. While breastfeeding has many benefits, your mental health matters too. Seek support early for challenges, and know that formula feeding is a perfectly healthy alternative if needed.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h6 class="mt-4">Postpartum Mental Health</h6>
          <p>Understanding the spectrum of postpartum mood disorders is essential for early recognition and treatment:</p>
          
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="card h-100">
                <div class="card-body">
                  <h6 class="card-title">Baby Blues</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Affects up to 80% of new mothers</li>
                    <li>Begins 2-3 days after delivery</li>
                    <li>Lasts up to two weeks</li>
                    <li>Symptoms: Mood swings, tearfulness, irritability, anxiety</li>
                    <li>Management: Rest, support, reassurance</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="card h-100">
                <div class="card-body">
                  <h6 class="card-title">Postpartum Depression (PPD)</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Affects 1 in 7 new mothers</li>
                    <li>Can begin anytime in first year</li>
                    <li>Symptoms: Persistent sadness, extreme fatigue, withdrawal, feelings of worthlessness, difficulty bonding</li>
                    <li>Management: Professional help, therapy, medication, support groups</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="card h-100">
                <div class="card-body">
                  <h6 class="card-title">Postpartum Anxiety</h6>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Often occurs alongside PPD</li>
                    <li>Symptoms: Constant worry, racing thoughts, difficulty sleeping even when baby sleeps, physical symptoms (nausea, heart racing)</li>
                    <li>Management: Professional help, cognitive behavioral therapy, medication when appropriate</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
            <p class="mb-0"><strong>Seek immediate help if experiencing:</strong> Thoughts of harming yourself or baby, hallucinations or delusions, extreme confusion, or inability to function. These may be signs of postpartum psychosis, which requires emergency treatment.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Newborn Care Basics</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="newbornAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFeeding">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFeeding" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFeeding">
                  Feeding & Nutrition
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseFeeding" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFeeding" data-bs-parent="#newbornAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> Newborns need to feed 8-12 times per day (every 2-3 hours)</li>
                    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Breastfeeding sessions typically last 20-40 minutes total</li>
                    <li><strong>Hunger cues:</strong> Rooting, hand-to-mouth, sucking motions, fussiness</li>
                    <li><strong>Adequate intake signs:</strong> 6+ wet diapers daily, regular bowel movements, content between feedings, steady weight gain</li>
                    <li><strong>Burping:</strong> Try halfway through and after each feeding</li>
                    <li><strong>Formula preparation:</strong> Always follow manufacturer instructions for mixing and storage</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingSleep">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseSleep" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSleep">
                  Sleep & Safety
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseSleep" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingSleep" data-bs-parent="#newbornAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p><strong>Safe Sleep Guidelines:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Always place baby on back to sleep</li>
                    <li>Use firm sleep surface in safety-approved crib or bassinet</li>
                    <li>Keep soft objects, loose bedding, bumpers out of sleep area</li>
                    <li>Room-sharing recommended for at least first 6 months</li>
                    <li>Bed-sharing not recommended</li>
                    <li>Consider pacifier for sleep after breastfeeding is established</li>
                    <li>Maintain smoke-free environment</li>
                    <li>Avoid overheating baby</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <p><strong>Newborn Sleep Patterns:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Newborns sleep 14-17 hours in 24-hour period</li>
                    <li>Sleep occurs in 2-4 hour stretches</li>
                    <li>Day/night confusion common in early weeks</li>
                    <li>Sleep needs gradually decrease over first year</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingDiapering">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseDiapering" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseDiapering">
                  Diapering & Hygiene
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseDiapering" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingDiapering" data-bs-parent="#newbornAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p><strong>Diapering:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Expect 6-10 wet diapers and 3-4 bowel movements daily in first month</li>
                    <li>Change diapers promptly when wet or soiled</li>
                    <li>Clean genital area thoroughly with each change</li>
                    <li>For girls, wipe front to back</li>
                    <li>For uncircumcised boys, never force foreskin back</li>
                    <li>Allow air time to help prevent diaper rash</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <p><strong>Bathing:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Sponge baths until umbilical cord stump falls off (1-3 weeks)</li>
                    <li>Bathe 2-3 times per week (more frequent bathing can dry skin)</li>
                    <li>Use mild, fragrance-free soap</li>
                    <li>Water temperature should be warm, not hot (100°F/38°C)</li>
                    <li>Never leave baby unattended in bath</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <p><strong>Umbilical Cord Care:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Keep area clean and dry</li>
                    <li>Fold diaper below stump</li>
                    <li>Clean with water if soiled</li>
                    <li>Avoid covering with bandages</li>
                    <li>Contact provider if signs of infection (redness, odor, discharge)</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingHealth">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseHealth" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseHealth">
                  Health & Development
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseHealth" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingHealth" data-bs-parent="#newbornAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p><strong>Well-Baby Visits:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>First visit: 3-5 days after birth</li>
                    <li>Regular schedule: 1 month, 2 months, 4 months, 6 months, 9 months, 12 months</li>
                    <li>Includes weight and growth checks, development assessment, vaccinations</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <p><strong>When to Call the Doctor:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Fever (100.4°F/38°C or higher)</li>
                    <li>Poor feeding (refuses multiple feedings)</li>
                    <li>Decreased wet diapers (fewer than 6 in 24 hours)</li>
                    <li>Inconsolable crying or unusual fussiness</li>
                    <li>Difficulty breathing</li>
                    <li>Vomiting (not just spitting up)</li>
                    <li>Diarrhea</li>
                    <li>Extreme sleepiness or difficulty waking</li>
                  </ul>
                  
                  <p><strong>Developmental Milestones (First 3 Months):</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Lifts head when on tummy</li>
                    <li>Follows objects with eyes</li>
                    <li>Responds to sounds</li>
                    <li>Begins to smile socially</li>
                    <li>Starts cooing and making sounds</li>
                    <li>Recognizes familiar faces</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
