      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Postpartum Recovery Supplies</h5>
          
          <p>Prepare your postpartum recovery kit with these essentials:</p>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">For Physical Recovery</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Maxi pads (heavy flow, no tampons)</li>
            <li>Perineal cold packs</li>
            <li>Peri bottle for cleansing</li>
            <li>Witch hazel pads/wipes</li>
            <li>Sitz bath or basin</li>
            <li>Pain relievers (approved by provider)</li>
            <li>Stool softeners</li>
            <li>Comfortable, high-waisted underwear</li>
            <li>Nursing bras & breast pads</li>
            <li>Nipple cream (if breastfeeding)</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">For Comfort & Convenience</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Easy, front-opening clothes</li>
            <li>Nursing pillow (helpful for C-section recovery too)</li>
            <li>Water bottle with straw</li>
            <li>Healthy snacks for one-handed eating</li>
            <li>Phone charger with extra-long cord</li>
            <li>Basket of essentials for each floor of home</li>
            <li>Heating pad for afterpains</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
            <p class="mb-0"><strong>Tip:</strong> Prepare freezer meals before baby arrives, and don't hesitate to accept help with meals, cleaning, or baby care when offered.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Partners in Parenting</h5>
          
          <p>Support for non-birthing partners is essential for family bonding and parental wellbeing.</p>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Ways Partners Can Support</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Learn baby care skills (diapering, burping, bathing)</li>
            <li>Take night shifts with pumped milk or formula</li>
            <li>Manage household responsibilities</li>
            <li>Screen visitors and protect family bonding time</li>
            <li>Advocate for mother's needs during recovery</li>
            <li>Practice skin-to-skin contact with baby</li>
            <li>Watch for signs of postpartum depression/anxiety</li>
            <li>Attend pediatrician appointments</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Partner Mental Health</h6>
          <p>Non-birthing parents can also experience adjustment difficulties, including:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Sleep deprivation</li>
            <li>Anxiety about new responsibilities</li>
            <li>Stress about financial changes</li>
            <li>Feelings of exclusion during breastfeeding</li>
            <li>Paternal postpartum depression (affects 8-10% of fathers)</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p>Seek support through parenting groups, counseling, or speaking with healthcare providers if struggling.</p>
        </div>
